Hey Chet,<br><br>
REMF is a word I never liked to use. <br><br>
One reason why I never display my medals is because I am conscientious about the feelings of others, namely those who were not in the same circumstances as I was. I was infantry. <br><br>
My last 3 months (I got a 30 drop from my tour,hallelujah!) in RVN were served as the Battalion Psyops NCO and the Reenlistment NCO. When I got reassigned I felt I was 1 step closer to home. I honestly can say that was my central thought. My replacement was an E6 and he was my *subordinate* for a month while I continued, as an E5, to run the mortar platoon.<br><br>
I had tears in my eyes when I gave away all my gear to my buds with whom I served all those months. When the chopper came to OP George to take my ass to the rear, I felt the sincere, understanding, and even happy (for me) best wishes from those guys. They were glad for me.<br><br>
Understand one thing. I was DRAFTED into that damned mess. However, I was determined to make the best out of my military service - which I did. I served.<br><br>
The greatest compliment I ever received came from one of the guys I served with, when he simply said, &quot;You took good care of us&quot;. All the guys in the mortar platoon made it back alive.<br><br>
I was NOT a &quot;warrior&quot;.  Fuck the war. I was a young kid who was determined to make it back home. That was my central thought. The connotation of the word &quot;warrior&quot; is consistent with a belief in the war. I did not believe in the Vietnam War - even though I fought in it.<br><br>
A funny thing is that I never felt shame about my serving in Vietnam. Never felt that I was better than anyone else either.<br><br>

